Jeff's chauvinist father (Brian Dennehy), who expects Audrey to wait on him hand and foot, extends his visit after spraining his ankle.
Jeff and Audrey lie to get out of going to a party that Jennifer and Adam are hosting; Russell ticks off Jerry Rice.

Jeff invites Audrey to watch him play softball, hoping to show her that he's not an old fogey.

Russell ropes his new assistant Timmy into helping him win a bet.
Audrey invites a friend (Tony Hale) to stay with her and Jeff after discovering that his marriage is in trouble.
Jeff and Audrey go on a double date with Brad and Jackie; Russell goes on a date with a psychiatrist.
After Jennifer hosts a party, Jeff wonders if he and Audrey are lacking adventure in their personal life.
Audrey tries to convince Jeff that they should use the money he made from selling his car for something fun.
Jeff and Audrey's idea of the perfect candidate to serve as their surrogate is ruined.
Jeff brags to Adam about a list he keeps of mistakes that Audrey has made; Russell sends a suggestive e-mail to a co-worker.
When Audrey gives their rug to Adam and Jenn, Jeff tries to sabotage the gift by telling Adam about all the ``fun'' he and Audrey had on it.
Audrey tries to be more spontaneous with Jeff in the bedroom; Russell invites Timmy to join him on a business trip to distract him from his fear of flying.
Audrey contemplates quitting her job after realizing how miserable it makes her; Allison tells Timmy she wants to slow things down.
Leslie and Justin reunite her mother with an old flame for Valentine's Day; Andy's band is nervous about playing a gig at the Senior Center.
When a neighboring town puts a fence around one of its parks, Leslie asks an old friend for help; Ron tries to stop his own birthday party from happening.
Ann's lack of enthusiasm at an offer for a city hall job causes an argument with Leslie; Tom invites everyone to help him promote his new alcoholic beverage.
Leslie and the Parks Department organize a memorial for a dearly departed friend; Tom makes a big decision; Chris reacts poorly to a health issue.
Leslie uses her new tourist attraction to spend more time with Ben; Ron and April encourage Andy to further his education; Chris assigns a logo redesign to Tom and Jerry.
Leslie and Ben defend themselves against Chris' ethics charges.
Leslie forms a citizen action group in hope of getting some work done; everyone in the office tries to plan a Christmas gift for Leslie.
Leslie asks for help staging an event; Ben gets a new hobby; April and Andy adopt a pet.
Leslie and Ben disagree about her campaign ad; Chris makes Ron uncomfortable; Andy and April go to the doctor.
After receiving feedback from a focus group, Leslie and Ben plan a casual bowling party; April, Jerry and Chris compete to see who can raise the most money for Leslie's campaign.

Leslie holds a sex-education class following an STD outbreak among senior citizens in Pawnee; when Tom's gadgets are taken away, Ron helps him acclimate to life without technology; April and Ben meet Congressman Murray.
April and Leslie try to get more women hired in government; Tom asks Ben and Andy to teach him about basketball; Ron watches Diane's kids.
Leslie tries to help a failing video store stay open; Chris advises Tom on dealing with a difficult employee; Ann tries to force April to be her friend.
Ben, Leslie and Chris meet with Eagleton city councilor Ingrid de Forest (Kristen Bell) to discuss financial matters; Ann brings April to vet school orientation; Ron tries to get off the grid.
Pawnee Parks employees are paired up with their Eagleton counterparts; Chris and Ben work on an accounting project together; Ann divulges her plans.
An emergency late-night filibuster forces Leslie to leave Ben's birthday party early; Tom tries to create memories with his girlfriend; Ron and Donna go hunting; April and Andy reconnect.
On the day of the recall vote, Leslie works on a haunted house with Ben, Chris and Ann; Tom asks Ron for help saving his business.
Leslie tries to tackle some of her goals, such as hosting an event with the Indianapolis Colts and adding fluoride to Pawnee's drinking water; Chris and Ron build cribs together.
Leslie faces off with Councilman Jamm; Ben gets a new hobby; Tom, April and Donna help Ron sell his cabin.
Leslie makes plans for her future with Ben as she comes to term with her last day in office; Ann and Chris learn the sex of their baby; Chris returns from London.

Leslie and Ben start new jobs; Donna, April and Andy prank Ben; Tom readies himself for a big presentation; Ann and Chris consider the future.
Leslie and Ben argue over sales techniques at the farmers market; Ann looks for a way to let off steam about the annoying parts of pregnancy; April backs Andy in a new creative venture.
Leslie throws a goodbye party for Ann and Chris and tries to fulfill a promise; the guys search for a going-away gift for Chris.

Leslie's efforts to take down the wall separating Eagleton and Pawnee yield unexpected results; Ben and Tom meet with possible sponsors for the concert; Ron finds a new hobby.

Leslie runs afoul of local shock jocks when she creates a new town slogan; Andy discovers an interesting secret about Ron while scouting for bands to play the Unity Concert; Tom, Donna and April look for a restaurant locale.
Leslie throws a Galentine's Day in an effort to find a new friend; Tom and Ben try to secure tents for the concert; Ron looks after Andy.
Leslie helps organize the senior prom at the high school; Andy takes April as his date, despite her objections; Ben helps Tom with music at the prom.
Ben and Leslie organize a charity fund to raise money for the concert; April manages Andy's schedule; Donna turns to Ron for help with an ex-boyfriend (Keegan-Michael Key).
A 23-year-old man must enlist his family to help him raise a baby that is the result of a one-night stand with a wanted felon.
Jimmy asks Sabrina's cousin (Kate Micucci) to baby-sit Hope so he can return to work; Burt tries to persuade Virginia to quit smoking.
The family baby-proofs the house as Hope learns to crawl; Jimmy frequently visits the grocery store in hopes of seeing Sabrina.
Jimmy realizes that he has no family photos that include Hope, so he organizes a family photo shoot.
A box of videos of Hope's mother arrives from prison; Jimmy questions what his parents have kept from him.
When Sabrina's boyfriend can't make it to a Halloween party, Jimmy offers to put on his costume and go in his place; Virginia takes Maw Maw, dressed as a cat, trick or treating.

When Hope catches a cold, Virginia panics because the family does not have health insurance; Jimmy figures out a way to get a second job at Sabrina's grocery store so he can afford to take Hope to the pediatrician.
When Hope starts imitating dogs at her day care, Jimmy tries to enroll her in a high-end center, but a blemish on Burt's record must first be expunged before she can be accepted.
Jimmy invites Hope's other grandparents to join his family for Thanksgiving dinner, but they kidnap the baby, and the Chances must track her down.
Jimmy learns he was a musical prodigy until an accident ruined his talent, and asks Burt, Virginia and Maw Maw to help him recover his abilities.
Burt lets the family in on some information he learned about Sabrina; the Chance family meets Sabrina's father.
When a man who kidnapped Burt 20 years earlier comes to visit, new light is shed on the incident; Jimmy makes Sabrina uncomfortable.
When Jimmy meets a woman, Mary Louise (Ashley Tisdale), in improv class, she agrees to pretend to date him in hope of making Sabrina jealous.
Virginia tries to use her experience and Burt's to help a client's teenage daughter; Jimmy and Sabrina play along when Maw Maw mistakes Jimmy for her late husband.
When Jimmy and Sabrina agree to be completely honest with each other, an unusual childhood phobia is revealed; Burt tells Virginia about his secret habit.
Virginia convinces Jimmy that Sabrina is doing more than school work with her new study partner; Burt becomes obsessed with a wall figurine.
When Jimmy leaves Hope with Sabrina for the day, Sabrina tries to prove her parenting skills; Virginia and Burt try to catch a squirrel bully.
When Jimmy and Sabrina decide to buy a new car, they learn Burt and Virginia ruined Jimmy's credit when he was a child.
Jimmy participates in medical experiments to raise money for an engagement ring; when Jimmy finds the perfect ring at a pawn shop, it ends up being Virginia's.
Jimmy is apprehensive when Frank wants to throw a memorable bachelor party; Sabrina encourages Jimmy to cut loose and have fun.

The whole family goes on a road trip to Los Angeles for a taping of Hope's favorite show, ``Yo Zappa Do''; Virginia and Burt let Ricardo stay at their place, but their house guest quickly wears out his welcome.
When Hope and Jimmy start working on ``Yo Zappa Do,'' the show's star makes Jimmy's life miserable.
When Sabrina learns Jimmy never went on a family vacation, she decides to take Hope on a trip and prove to Burt and Virginia that family vacations aren't necessarily stressful.

When Virginia gets new glasses, she discovers good vision only allows her to see all the imperfections around the house; Jimmy and Sabrina take advantage of Maw Maw's zaniness in an effort to get more followers on a social media site.
The new owner of Howdy's wants all the employees come up with ideas to change the store.
Burt and Virginia work to expose a scandal that is killing Natesville's bees.
The family argues over Danny's questionable tactics as he searches for a missing girl; Jamie starts his new life as a cop.
A good Samaritan with a police record takes action against a terrorizing subway criminal, forcing the Reagans to weigh the rights and wrongs of vigilantism.
Danny, Erin and Frank work together to seek justice when the main suspect in a rape case is protected by diplomatic immunity.
When an off-duty police officer is killed during a diamond heist, the entire NYPD searches for the person responsible.
Three teenagers die from drug overdose, and Danny sets out to find their narcotic source and bring the responsible to justice.
The family questions Erin's tactics when she tries to take down a gang leader by using his law-abiding brother as bait.
After witnessing a crime in progress, Jamie pursues a suspect; Danny has to help Jamie avoid an internal affairs investigation.
Erin becomes the subject of a personal and deadly vendetta when a reviled rapist and murderer she put away is released from jail.
Danny investigates when a doorman at a nightclub is murdered; Frank makes a decision about a former partner's future.
Frankly gets a very close call when a stranger tries to take him out, consequently a manhunt across the city unfolds.
A young girl is murdered at a debutante ball; Danny gets into an fight with his sister for bringing Nikki to a crime scene.
In an effort to expose the Blue Templar, Frank decides not to report a drug bust case that reveals dirty cops.
Frank is put on the spot when one of the mayor-elect's supporters is found dead; Jamie goes under cover at a bar.
Danny makes a discovery about an attempted bank robber's past; Jamie starts working with a new partner (Monica Raymund).
Danny must face an internal affairs investigation after shooting a cop who failed to identify himself.
Erin reopens a rape case Frank worked on 18 years ago; when three teens are murdered, Jackie and Danny can't determine an obvious motive.
Danny tries to investigate a case while having a romantic weekend with Linda; Jamie goes under cover to infiltrate a crime family.
Jamie and Renzulli are injured by a church's security team while responding to a 911 call, and Frank must deal with the fallout.
Danny and his family have an encounter with a gunman; Frank prepares to say goodbye to a friend he worked with at ground zero.
Jackie and Danny look into the suspicious death of an investor; when the Sanfinos order a hit on Jimmy Riordan, Frank puts Jamie under house arrest.

When two different people driving gas-guzzling vehicles are killed by a sniper, the city thinks a radical environmental serial killer is responsible; Danny's son is severely injured in a bicycle accident.
Jamie's career hangs in the balance when he shoots an armed man in a tourist spot, leading Danny to conduct an investigation into the gunman.
When Danny is pulled over because his car matches the description of one involved in a drug deal, police find cocaine in his trunk; Danny's family rallies to come to his defense.
When an incident in the projects leads to the death of a 10-year-old boy, Danny's reaction lands him in anger-management class; Frank tries to help a young Turkish woman avoid persecution.
Danny and Erin investigate a cold case in which a rich and powerful man allegedly attacked his girlfriend; an injury during a pick-up game leads to a lawsuit.
An off-duty cop is disarmed by bank robbers and an innocent bystander is wounded; Frank starts to fall for a woman from ACLU.
When the same tragedy occurs to multiple people in New York, Danny must determine what connects them and who is responsible; Frank tries to help a friend face his alcoholism.
When a devout young woman is murdered, Danny questions her family; a secret relationship is uncovered.
When a family friend is murdered, the Reagans band together to take down the leader of the gang responsible; a second crisis sends Frank reeling.
When two Wall Street brokers are killed during drug deals, Linda bars Danny from questioning a wounded accomplice until after the man has had surgery.
Danny is suspicious when he encounters a disoriented man covered in blood; Jamie helps an off-duty officer conceal his intoxication after apprehending an armed robber.
Danny is upset when a woman he promised to help commits suicide; the Reagan family suffers a loss due to a gang.
Famous movie star Russell Berke (Marc Blucas), who researched a role by shadowing Danny, becomes the victim of a stabbing.
Danny serves as lead hostage negotiator when Erin is held at gunpoint inside the courtroom; when Jamie is suspended for disobeying orders, Frank must determine a proper punishment.
A teen girl dies after she is seemingly pushed in front of a subway car by a homeless man; Frank is irritated by having to meet with the new inspector general (Bebe Neuwirth).
Danny and Baez think a girl has been kidnapped, but her mother denies it; Frank visits a priest who was arrested for a DUI.
Jamie's conduct is questioned when a suspect he was pursuing is fatally injured; Baez goes under cover to investigate a drug dealer -- the fiance of Danny's ex-girlfriend (Charisma Carpenter).
The community and the mayor scrutinize Frank's department when an officer is accused of using excessive force; a Wall Street executive who was deeply in debt is murdered.
Baez's estranged brother is the primary suspect in a homicide; a woman may have had a hand in her husband's death.
Danny and Baez meet with resistance while investigating a bombing; Frank deals with political fallout after a man punches an aggressive officer.
Danny tracks the distributor of a new, deadly type of heroin; Frank does everything he can to help Danny get the drug off the streets.
A kidnapping investigation brings back bad memories for Danny, who worked a similar case years ago; Frank and Inspector General Peterson butt heads.
